For those who don't know, the skinny is, you want better service, you have to pay more for it now.<br>
In essence, that means you are paying a premium for what was previously free. <br>
The service isn't necessarily better, you just won't be talked at with a frown, your call will be answered quicker and you will basically have your booty liberally kissed.<br>
I work for a very large scale travel agency, in the after hours service. There are different levels that one can pay for, but in the long run, it's the same product.<br>
<br>
So, in the years to come, if you are an average guy, expect to speak to fewer human beings, increased ignorance by cs agents, and very little recourse for bad service.<br>
<br>
oh well... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/urexron.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rexron</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Pie Guy </span><br>  Posts: 132<br> <font color=#333333>(5/1/01 11:25:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=32.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My flame on tiered customer service</span><hr size=1> Cro-mag,<br>
Unfortunately, you are right.  However, it's a matter of cost consciousness.  <br>
<br>
When it comes to running lean, customer service is something that with a little capital outlay, can be a reduced cost over the long run.  While pressing 4 or 5 buttons sucks, and hanging on the phone to get my ISP CS for over 30 minutes during a QUIET time sucks more ... i find my rates reasonable, and dont think i'd wanna pay another $5 or $10 a month for that to be a 10 min wait instead of 30.<br>
<br>
Cost/Benefit .. does the benefit outweight the cost.  If not, then dont do.<br>
